<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1059,874,984]" pageId="53" pageNumber="1012">
D i a g n o s i s: The elytral apex is yellow, the pronotum slightly oblong, the pronotal disc is broadly black, and elytral asetiferous punctures are arranged into 9 striae. The combination of these characteristics will distinguish the members of this species from congeners. The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1950" box="[378,502,962,983]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="53" pageNumber="1019" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[378,502,962,983]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="1012">Pujoliclerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
PIC was revised in 2014 (
<bibRefCitation author="OPITZ W" box="[764,900,962,984]" pageId="53" pageNumber="1012" pagination="727 - 756" refId="ref53564" refString="OPITZ W. (2014 d): Classification, natural history, and evolution of the checkered beetle genus Pujoliclerus PIC (Coleoptera: Cleridae: Peloniinae). - The Coleopteristss Bulletin 68 (4): 727 - 756." type="journal article" year="2014">OPITZ 2014d</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1059,999,1344]" pageId="53" pageNumber="1012">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 4.0 mm; width 
<quantity box="[673,753,999,1021]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="53" pageNumber="1012" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[895,980,999,1021]" captionStart="Figs 338-341" captionStartId="112.[151,191,1510,1532]" captionTargetBox="[155,1060,195,1490]" captionTargetId="figure@112.[153,1061,195,1493]" captionTargetPageId="112" captionText="Figs 338-341: Habitus; (338) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (339) P. catie; (340) P. cnecostus; (341) P. convexus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746830" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746830/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="1012">Fig. 339</figureCitation>
. Color: Cranium mostly testaceous, upper frons and epicranium with black broad line at middle; antenna black; prothorax mostly yellow, pronotal disc mostly black, upper angles yellow; pterothorax and abdomen dark brown; elytra mostly dark brown, apex yellow; legs bicolorous, become less infuscated from prothoracic legs to metathoracic legs. Head: Cranium coarsely punctate; antenna (
<figureCitation box="[556,638,1146,1168]" captionStart="Figs 1-27" captionStartId="70.[151,191,1302,1324]" captionTargetBox="[155,1057,207,1268]" captionTargetId="figure@70.[155,1058,207,1283]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="Figs 1-27: Antennae; (1) Aphelocerus nodus; (2) A. copanus; (3) A. magnipannus; (4) A. yoro; (5) A. sparicapillus; (6) A. tigra. (7) A. nolus; (8) A. ligulus; (9) Perilypus schusteri; (10) P. apunctus; (11) P. virgulatus; (12) P. izabal; (13) P. alpinus; (14) Cregya fuscomacula; (15) Phonius versus; (16) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (17) Pelonium falcatum; (18) Pujoliclerus cnecostus; (19) P. trunculus. (20) P. sentus; (21) P. testudinatus; (22) P. catie; (23) P. flavidus; (24) P. convexus; (25) P. meloinus; (26) P. mexicoensis; (27) P. tuxtlas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746746/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="1012">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
) capitate, funicular antennomeres subserrate, 6 
<superScript attach="left" box="[247,260,1171,1185]" fontSize="6" pageId="53" pageNumber="1012">th</superScript>
antennomere expanded, capitular antennomeres 8 and 9 triangular, antennomere 10 ovate; eyes large, coarsely facetted, eye wider than frons (EW/FW 20/15). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[361,453,1234,1256]" captionStart="Figs 134-152" captionStartId="77.[151,191,1476,1498]" captionTargetBox="[183,1049,204,1454]" captionTargetId="figure@77.[152,1060,199,1462]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="Figs 134-152: Pronota; (134) Pujoliclerus catie; (135) P. mexicoensis; (136) P. convexus; (137) P. testudinatus; (138) Madoniella selvanegra; (139) Cregya entrerios; (140) Pujoliclerus trunculus; (141) P. sentus; (142) P. meloinus; (143) Sicamus suprus; (144) Nepsudia guenda; (145) Nanoclerus fuscus; (146) Topainca pachacutii; (147) Eurycaulis anaxeis; (148) Kataspinula puebla; (149) Madoniella muralla; (150) M. nota; (151) M. acicula; (152) M. baja." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746760" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746760/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="1012">Fig. 134</figureCitation>
) slightly oblong (PW/PL 55/60), disc coarsely punctate, lateral tubercles well developed; elytral asetiferous punctures organized into 9 striae, punctures diminish near elytral apex (EL/EW 170/40). Abdomen: Pygidium quadrate 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1051,1058,1292,1314]" pageId="53" pageNumber="1012">/</emphasis>
scutiform, posterior margin incised; aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[673,765,1322,1344]" captionStart="Figs 249-254" captionStartId="91.[151,191,1289,1311]" captionTargetBox="[155,1061,201,1276]" captionTargetId="figure@91.[155,1061,201,1276]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="Figs 249-254: Aedeagi; (249) Pujoliclerus catie; (250) P. dexus; (251) P. meloinus; (252) P. mexicoensis (253) P. testudinatus (254) P. trunculus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746788" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746788/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="1012">Fig. 249.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
